%N A327854 Value of the critical density of the Universe in g/cm^3 multiplied by dimensionless scale factor h^(-2).
%C A327854 The critical density is defined as p_c = 3*H^2/8*Pi*G, where H is the Hubble constant and G is the gravitational constant (A070058) (cf. ESA, Critical density).
%C A327854 The critical density is the value of matter density that ensures the expansion of the Universe eventually halts, but the Universe does not recollapse in a "Big Crunch". This is often expressed via a density parameter Omega, defined as Omega = p/p_c, where p is the actual matter density of the Universe. Thus the Universe is "open", "flat" or "closed", depending on whether Omega < 1, Omega = 1 or Omega > 1. Observations suggest that the dark energy density Omega_Lambda and matter density Omega_m add to a value close to 1 (cf. Planck Collaboration, 2013).
%H A327854 R. Aldrovandi, J. Gariel and G. Marcilhacy, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0203079">On the pre-nucleosynthesis cosmological period</a>, arXiv:gr-qc/0203079 [gr-qc], 2002.
